<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="55" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="55">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="55">
Based on the illustrations (Figs 1-19) and description by Ding and Chen (2001), this species can be distinguished from other species of the genus by the following characters: pygofer with three medioventral processes; anal segment without process, suspensorium ring-shaped. This species is also similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Indozuriel" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Indozuriel rostri" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostri">Indozuriel rostri</taxonomicName>
Ding &amp; Zhou, 1973 in appearance, but can be easily distinguished from the latter by the parameres without curved apically (parameres with curved apically in 
<taxonomicName genus="I." lsidName="I. rostri" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="rostri">I. rostri</taxonomicName>
). This species is also similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Javesella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Javesella salina" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salina">Javesella salina</taxonomicName>
(Haupt, 1924) in the shaped of aedeagus, but can be easily distinguished from the latter by the pygofer having a medioventral processes (pygofer without medioventral process in 
<taxonomicName genus="J." lsidName="J. salina" pageId="2" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="salina">J. salina</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
